# shuffle the data so class order isn't in order - need this for training/testing split later on 
titanic_set <- titanic_set[shuffle_index, ]

MVP

1

titanic_clean <- titanic_set %>% 
  drop_na(survived) %>% 
  mutate(sex = as.factor(sex),
         survived = factor(survived, 
                              levels = c(0,1), 
                              labels = c("No", "Yes")),
         pclass = factor(pclass, 
                            levels = c(3,2,1), 
                            labels = c("Lower", "Middle", "Upper")),
         embarked = as.factor(embarked),
         age_status = as.factor(if_else(age >= 16, "adult", "child"))) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  select(-X1, -passenger_id, -name, -ticket, -fare, -cabin, -age)

3

nrow_titanic <- nrow(titanic_clean)

test_index <- sample(1:nrow_titanic, size = nrow_titanic*0.2)
test_titanic <- slice(titanic_clean, test_index)
train_titanic <- slice(titanic_clean, -test_index)
  • Chose an 80/20 split
test_titanic %>% 
janitor::tabyl(survived)
##  survived  n percent
##        No  9    0.25
##       Yes 27    0.75
train_titanic %>% 
  janitor::tabyl(survived)
##  survived  n   percent
##        No 51 0.3469388
##       Yes 96 0.6530612
  • They are reasonably balanced

4

titanic_tree <- rpart(survived ~ .,
                      data = train_titanic,
                      method = "class")
rpart.plot(titanic_tree, 
           yesno = 2, 
           fallen.leaves = T, 
           faclen = 6, 
           digits = 4, 
           type = 4, 
           extra = 101)

5

1st variable: Sex - splits the data 50/50 - 70/74 women survived = higher survival chance - 29/73 Men survived

2nd variable (splits Males): Class - small number lower/middle class -> 6/10 survived = higher survival chance - 23/63 upper class survived

3rd variable (splits Upper Class): Port of embarkation - 39 for ports Q and S -> 11/39 survived - 24 for port C -> 12/24 survived = higher survival chance

4th variable (splits port C): Sibling/parents on board - 16 for 0 sibs/parents = 7/16 survived - 8 for >= 1 sib/parents = 5/8 survived = higher survival chance

  • Sex is the strongest predictor

  • Highest chance of survival are women.

  • Lowest chance is a man, in upper class, who boarded at Queenstown or Southampton

6

titanic_test_pred <- test_titanic %>% 
  add_predictions(titanic_tree, type = "class")
 conf_mat <- titanic_test_pred %>% 
  conf_mat(truth = survived, estimate = pred)

conf_mat
##           Truth
## Prediction No Yes
##        No   6  11
##        Yes  3  16
  • High number for False Negatives
titanic_test_pred %>%
  sensitivity(truth = survived, estimate = pred)
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 sens    binary         0.667
titanic_test_pred %>%
  specificity(truth = survived, estimate = pred)
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 spec    binary         0.593
  • Decent sensitivity (True Positive Rate)
  • Poor specificity (True Negative Rate)

Extension

titanic_tree2 <- rpart(survived ~ .,
                      data = train_titanic,
                      method = "class",
                      control = rpart.control(
                        minsplit = 2,
                        minbucket = 1))
rpart.plot(titanic_tree2, 
           yesno = 2, 
           fallen.leaves = T, 
           faclen = 6, 
           digits = 4, 
           type = 4, 
           extra = 101)

titanic_test_pred2 <- test_titanic %>% 
  add_predictions(titanic_tree2, type = "class")
 conf_mat2 <- titanic_test_pred2 %>% 
  conf_mat(truth = survived, estimate = pred)

conf_mat2
##           Truth
## Prediction No Yes
##        No   6  10
##        Yes  3  17
titanic_test_pred2 %>%
  sensitivity(truth = survived, estimate = pred)
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>

## # A tibble: 1 x 3

##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 spec    binary         0.630

  • Adds in Age status to splits males = yes

  • Adds in number of parents to split siblings/spouses >= 1

  • Similar TPP (sensitivity) and TNP (specificity) to original model
